<p>Identify the one question your customers ask that you can answer better than anyone else. Make that answer the best resource on the internet for that specific query. Do not spread thin across 50 mediocre posts. Go deep on one topic where you have real authority.</p>
<p>For <a href="/blog/seo-small-business-guide/">local SEO</a>, this means combining your content expertise with local signals. The medical group did not just write a generic health article. They tied it to their practice, their physicians, and their geographic market.</p>
<h2>Case Study 3: Marco — 2,500% Growth Through Consistent Publishing &#123;#case-study-3-marco&#125;</h2>
<p>Marco is a B2B company in the meeting room technology space. Their market is niche. Their audience is specific. And their competitors were already publishing regularly.</p>
<h3>The Strategy</h3>
<p>Marco committed to a high-volume publishing schedule. They published 16 to 20 blog posts per month, every month, for a full year. Each post targeted a specific keyword their ideal customer searched. The content was not generic. It addressed real problems their sales team heard on calls.</p>
<p>The strategy had three parts:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Intent-driven keyword research</strong> — Every post matched a specific stage of the buyer journey</li>
<li><strong>Consistent publishing velocity</strong> — 16 to 20 posts per month without gaps</li>
<li><strong>Internal linking structure</strong> — New posts connected to relevant product and category pages</li>
</ol>
<p>This is where most businesses fail. They publish 5 posts in month one, 2 in month two, and nothing in month three. Marco treated content like a product feature. It shipped on schedule.</p>
