<h2>How to Apply These Lessons to Your Business &#123;#how-to-apply&#125;</h2>
<p>Reading case studies is motivating. Acting on them is harder. Here is a 90-day framework to apply what these five businesses proved.</p>
<h3>Step 1: Audit Your Current State</h3>
<p>Before you publish another post, know where you stand. Run a <a href="/blog/seo-audit-checklist/">technical SEO audit</a>. Check your Core Web Vitals. Identify your top 10 traffic-driving pages. Identify your worst-performing pages.</p>
<p>Most businesses have content debt. Old posts that rank for nothing. Thin pages that waste crawl budget. Fix these before adding new content.</p>
<h3>Step 2: Identify Your One Scalable Content Format</h3>
<p>What question do your customers ask repeatedly? What search could you answer better than anyone else? Pick one format and commit to it.</p>
<ul>
<li>Local business: Neighborhood or service-area guides</li>
<li>B2B SaaS: Use case or comparison pages</li>
<li>E-commerce: Product category or buying guides</li>
<li>Professional services: FAQ or explainer resources</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Set a Publishing Velocity You Can Sustain</h3>
<p>Marco published 16 to 20 posts per month. That is aggressive. Most small businesses should aim for 8 to 12 quality posts per month. The key is consistency, not volume.</p>
<p>If you cannot sustain 8 posts per month internally, use <a href="/blog/seo-automation-tools/">SEO automation tools</a> or a done-for-you service. A sporadic publishing schedule is worse than no publishing at all.</p>
<h3>Step 4: Build Internal Links Between Related Content</h3>
<p>Every new post should link to 2 to 3 related posts on your site. Every existing post should receive links from new content. This builds topical authority and helps Google discover your pages.</p>
<p><a href="/blog/internal-linking-strategy/">Internal linking</a> is the most underused SEO tactic. It costs nothing and compounds over time.</p>
